the leader of bulgarias main opposition 
alliance tuesday predicted his group will take at least half the 
vote in the june 10 elections 
meanwhile the us embassy said ambassador sol polansky met in 
copenhagen with james a baker iii in response to a request by the 
us secretary of state to receive an assessment of the prospects 
for free and fair elections in bulgaria and in view of the 
increasing concern about the fairness of the electoral process 
baker and other foreign ministers of the 35nation conference on 
security and cooperation in europe are in denmark to attend a csce 
meeting 
udf chairman zhelyu zhelev made his electoral forecast in an 
interview after his alliance appeared to have suffered a setback 
because of controversial comments made by another opposition leader 
in the interview published in bulgaria and abroad milan 
drenchev head of the agrarian party nikola petkov was quoted as 
saying other udf leaders understand nothing about politics 
he reportedly announced his group would leave the opposition 
alliance after the june 17 runoff and would run independently in 
fall municipal elections 
officials of his party issued a denial tuesday and zhelev said 
drenchev was misquoted 
we believe we will win at least 50 percent we are aiming for 
more than that zhelev insisted despite widespread belief the 
ruling communists who now call themselves the socialist party 
would give the udf a close race 
he said attendance at recent opposition rallies was two to four 
times larger than that of comparable events organized by the ruling 
party 
while expressing confidence the voting process would be fair 
overall zhelev said he expects some attempts at manipulation 
the ruling party came to power with an election fraud with 
totally rigged elections in 1946 he declared it cannot 
reconcile itself with the thought of losing power 
western governments also have expressed interest recently in 
keeping the balloting fair 
apart from foreign observers of the voting including some from 
the united states other precautions have been taken the opposition 
leader said 
at least two udf representatives will be near each ballot box and 
free and fair election student activists will be posted in 1500 
polling stations about 10 percent of the total 
