<TEXT>
slovak nationalists who would 
like to create a separate state from the smaller of czechoslovakias 
two republics have campaigned aggressively and noisily for fridays 
elections the first free vote since 1946 
while their slovak national party is unlikely to finish higher 
than third in its native region their cause could become a major 
headache for the coalition governments likely to emerge at both 
federal and republican levels after the voting 
the chief task of the newly elected federal parliament in its 
twoyear term is to draft a new constitution deputies will have to 
address the thorny question of slovakias status 
all the parties campaigning in slovakia have adopted powerful 
local symbols slogans and heroes in election posters and ads 
the christian democrats frontrunners in slovakia although not 
nationwide say outright that they favor a shift from federation to 
a confederation that would loosen ties between two peoples whose 
languages are very similar but whose customs and history differ 
only foreign affairs defense and finance should be regulated at 
a national level in future said ivan carnogursky head of the 
slovak christian democrat movement 
according to his brother jan the christian democrats leading 
candidate in slovakia slovakia should ultimately enter a united 
europe as a separate state 
nobody is advocating a swift separation czech and slovak 
economies are too intertwined for that 
but the new freedom of speech and the full blast of an election 
campaign mean that ancient rivalry between the dominant czechs and 
the more rural slovaks who make up about onethird of 
czechoslovakias 155 million people is getting its fullest airing 
in more than 40 years 
in czechoslovakia a federation was formed in 1968 czechs 
resented it because it gave half the federal funds to a third of the 
people the 21year rule of gustav husak communist party chief 
later president and a slovak also brought an influx of slovaks to 
prague 
slovaks were not necessarily happy with what the federal money 
bought much of the industry devised by communist planners in the 
name of evening out economic inequities was unsuited to the rural 
region and blights the air and the eye around big cities such as the 
capital bratislava 
nationalist sentiment first broke out in spring when 
czechoslovakia decided to follow other newly liberated east european 
nations and remove socialist from the countrys name 
slovaks first insisted on a hyphen in the name to make a 
distinction between the czech and slovak regions thousands 
demonstrated angrily when the hyphen was not made obligatory in the 
czech republic 
the dispute eventually was settled by adopting the formal name 
czech and slovak federative republic for the country 
the clumsy solution pleased almost nobody and president vaclav 
havel a czech acknowledged that the name dispute had dispelled the 
euphoria engendered by last winters revolution 
about 500 slovak nationalists angrily disrupted havels final 
campaign appearance in bratislava on monday quieting down only when 
admonished by alexander dubcek the slovak hero of the 1968 prague 
spring he reminded them that totalitarianism had not been 
overthrown to make way for anarchy noting that democracy demanded 
they give the president a hearing 
earlier havel was interrupted several times during an appearance 
in southern slovakia at komarno 
latest opinion polls give the slovak national party just 7 
percent of the vote in the republic but in bratislava a 
centuriesold city with a tradition of more openness than slovakias 
sparsely populated mountains and valleys their support could go as 
high as 12 percent 
