soviet president mikhail s gorbachev may have 
returned to moscow bearing trade and arms agreements but he and his 
wife raisa were laden with other souvenirs as well including two 
of president bushs horseshoes 
among the many gifts the bushes gave the gorbachevs during the 
superpower summit was an orange pitching horseshoe mounted on a 
wooden plaque 
it was the lucky shoe that gorbachev had tossed for a firsttime 
ringer at camp david the presidential retreat in marylands 
catoctin mountains as he and his wife relaxed there last saturday 
with the bushes 
bush presented the horseshoe plaque to gorbachev at dinner that 
night 
but the next day a second horseshoe was discovered missing from 
the pit 
at first it wasnt clear what had happened but now the mystery 
has been solved 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said tuesday that 
mrs gorbachev who was with her husband when he pitched his ringer 
put the second horseshoe in her purse 
they took both he said 
fitzwater said mrs gorbachev had been invited to keep the second 
horseshoe which was the one that she had pitched by a bush aide 
the president later joked to members of his cabinet that 
gorbachevs visit had cost him two of his favorite horsehoes 
the horseshoeonaplaque gift was spontaneous a more formal 
exchange of gifts is part of every state visit 
considering how often bush meets with foreign leaders coming up 
with new gift ideas must strain the creativity of white house social 
planners 
the president gave gorbachev a fivevolume biography life of 
george washington by former chief justice john marshall in 
exchange the soviet leader gave bush an antique painting of russian 
birch trees 
mrs bush gave raisa gorbachev a goldandrhinestonetrimmed 
handbag in return she received an enameled tea set 
last year the gorbachevs gave the bushes a box of glass 
christmas ornaments and seven childrens books 
despite warming ussoviet relations american gifts to soviet 
leaders just arent what they used to be 
gorbachev got history books and a horseshoe former soviet leader 
leonid brezhnev was given a lincoln continental by thenpresident 
nixon at one of their summits 
sometimes gifts to and from foreign leaders can prove 
troublesome such as the two prized jaguars president andres 
rodriguez of paraguay gave vice president dan quayle earlier this 
year it turned out the cats were on the us endangered species 
list and no american zoo would take them 
quayle had to give them back he asked rodriguez to release them 
in the jungle 
and bush now may wish that he hadnt given leather cowboy boots 
bearing the flags of texas and china to chinese premier li peng he 
made the presentation when he visited beijing last year several 
months before government troops and tanks trampled prodemocracy 
demonstrators in tiananmen square 
us law permits federal officials from the president on down 
to keep gifts from foreign governments only with a value of 180 or 
less 
gifts worth more than that must be turned over to the state 
department for safekeeping 
barbara bush used to give a slide show when her husband was vice 
president when she would get to the slide of herself and the emir 
of bahrain she would tell audiences the agonized look on my face 
is because he had just given me 85000 worth of jewelry which i 
immediately gave to the state department 
it must be a coincidence but its remarkable how many public 
officials list gifts at just under that 180 threshold on their 
financial disclosure forms 
for instance vice president dan quayle and his wife marilyn gave 
these values on gifts from foreign governments in 1989 a picture 
and frame from the princess of thailand 170 a wooden carved bear 
from a highranking japanese official 175 a vase from the 
government of south korea 175 an engraved plate from el salvador 
175 
likewise white house chief of staff john sununu was able to keep 
the lacquered samovar two bottles of russian vodka and four ounces 
of black caviar that gorbachev gave him last year he valued the 
gifts at 173 
sig rogich assistant to the president for special activities 
got a like amount of caviar and vodka from gorbachev and an art 
book on impressionism as well his figured the combined value at 
178 
deputy national security adviser robert m gates reported 
receiving a cinnabar vase and wooden stand from the government of 
china he estimated their worth at 160 
fitzwater said there is a process under which foreign gifts worth 
more than 180 can be bought back from the government at auction 
but he said ill be honest with you ive pressed the state 
department for 25 years and have never been able to discover how in 
the world you do that 
as for himself fitzwater told reporters recently ive got a 
lacquered box from gorbachev thats my favorite gift i cant keep 
it because of the value but i can keep it on display in the white 
house so its in my office 
you can look at it any time you like he said 
