<TEXT>
hungry for more studies analyzing the big 
issues of our time but tired of the predictable pap from 
established research organizations 
clyde prestowitz has just what you need a new think tank but 
in a town with a think tank on nearly every corner a new kid on the 
block has to find a niche 
according to its creators the economic strategy institute will 
be the first research organization geared to the postcold war era 
a time when americas standing will be based not on its nuclear 
arsenal but on its ability to compete economically with countries 
such as japan 
when you consider the question of international trade and 
international economics virtually all of the think tanks are saying 
the same thing prestowitz told a news conference tuesday 
we see a vacuum out there in terms of useful analysis to help 
guide policymakers in an era that will be dominated by geoeconomics 
rather than geopolitics he said 
we are going to be the think tank of the 90s the think tank 
for america said ronald a morse the institutes executive vice 
president 
the institute hopes to use its 14 million in donations from 
corporations labor unions and foundations to promote productivity 
and competitiveness two current buzzwords in a country plagued by 
fears of declining ability to measure up in the global marketplace 
given prestowitzs history it is likely that the institutes 
views will be controversial a topranking trade negotiator during 
the reagan administrations first term he later wrote a 
bestselling book on his experiences titled trading places how we 
are giving our future to japan and how to reclaim it 
prestowitz charged in his book that wrongheaded policies caused 
soaring trade deficits and suggested that instead of trying to 
americanize the japanese system us policymakers should copy 
japans approach of fostering homegrown industry 
critics have accused prestowitz of promoting an americafirst 
approach to policymaking that could topple the world into a round of 
trade wars and protectionist barriers killing off the freetrade 
principles that have guided us policy since the end of world war 
ii 
prestowitz says labels such as protectionist and free trade are 
too simplistic 
neither of those labels exist in the real world the reality 
is somewhere in between he said we are trying to challenge the 
old shibboleths 
to address the countrys lagging competitiveness prestowitz said 
government needs to boost woefully low business investment and to 
reorient american corporations toward longerterm objectives 
the committee hosting tuesdays inaugural dinner for the 
institute included house majority leader richard gephardt dmo 
and senate republican leader bob dole of kansas 
dole said he saw the new institute as a wakeup call to 
american leaders who seem to think that our economic strength can 
continue to erode without threatening our national security our 
prosperity and our very way of life 
commerce secretary robert mosbacher who has lost several battles 
inside the administration pushing for more economic support for us 
industry sent best wishes 
among the new institutes financial backers are ford motor co 
chrysler corp trw inc and motorola inc among union backers are 
the aflcio the united auto workers and the united steelworkers 
prestowitz who has argued in the past about heavy japanese 
spending on washington lobbying said the institute had not received 
any financial backing from japan 
but we wouldnt turn it down if it showed up on our 
doorstep he said 
</TEXT>
