<TEXT>
for more than four decades west berliners 
have been stockpiling huge quantities of provisions to keep the city 
alive in case of another soviet blockade 
city officials now say that changing times have made the 
warehouses filled with sugar grain bandages toothpaste and 
hundreds of other items unnecessary 
this is a relic of the cold war said gerhard erbe the city 
official in charge of supervising a large portion of the emergency 
reserves 
the germans began stockpiling on the orders of the victorious 
western allies the united states france and britain after the 
berlin airlift broke the traumatic soviet blockade in may 1949 
west berlins leftist leaders say the federal government in bonn 
should ask the allies for permission to scrap the whole program for 
the city of 2 million people 
city government economics chief peter mitzscherling has even 
suggested giving the food and other supplies to eastern european 
nations where democracy has replaced cold war stalinism 
west berlin officials decline to give a breakdown of how much is 
stored saying its still kept top secret to keep the potential 
enemy from learning details of the plans 
the goal is in the event of another blockade to provide the 
city with all necessary goods erbe said it was also to have a 
calming effect on the people 
erbe said the goods stored in 200 separate locations are to 
last as rations for a long period of time but he declined to 
specify how long 
one of the storehouses is located in teeming westhafen along the 
spandau shipping canal where sacks of sugar medicines and 
thousands of cases of jarred of fruit are carefully stored 
horst kleffel who supervises part of the program for the federal 
government said the plan was to have enough food on hand for six 
months but he concedes that some things we now have in smaller 
quantities 
the berliner morgenpost newspaper has reported that 166444 tons 
of grain 38752 tons of canned vegetables and 493668 tons of light 
heating oil are stored the goods are routinely sold off and 
restocked to ensure that everything is usable 
over the years the stockpiled goods have provided great comfort 
to berliners especially the elderly who remember how their city 
was torn apart by the collapse of nazi germany in 1945 and shut off 
from the world by the soviet blockade three years later 
the soviets tried to starve the western part of the city into 
submission blocking passengers and traffic starting in june 1948 
for 10 months a massive western airlift organized by the united 
states kept the city alive 
even though the four power agreement of 1971 set aside many of 
the disputes with the soviets the emergency reserves stayed in this 
city 100 miles within thencommunist east germany 
the federal government in bonn provides about 125 million a year 
to maintain the reserves which could be worth up to 16 billion 
as officials look around to save money during the enormously 
expensive unification process the reserves have become a likely 
target for savings they have also been the subject of sarcasm 
the west berlin city government even wanted to start getting 
rid of the huge supplies of toilet paper since according to state 
secretary juergen dittberner people could just use a newspaper in 
an emergency the frankfurter rundschau quoted the citys no 2 
economics official as saying 
but at the prompting of the federal government the toilet 
paper stayed the newspaper said 
chancellor helmut kohls government must study the request to 
halt the program before deciding whether to pass it on to the 
western allies 
anthony w sariti us diplomatic spokesman in berlin said it 
is not certain what answer the allies will give but given the 
tenor of the times i cant imagine we would give it unsympathetic 
hearing 
selling off the stockpiles could take three or more years 
the list of stockpiled items includes soap cleaning materials 
coffee fish meat as well as clothing for children erbe said one 
thing is missing dog food to feed berliners adored pooches 
people would have to share their own rations with their dogs 
he said with a laugh 
</TEXT>
