<TEXT>
children face far greater risks from global 
pollution than do adults a united nations report says 
children are too often the victims of pollution their young 
bodies make them far more vulnerable than adults to the poisons we 
spew into the air and toxins we sow on earth said the unicef 
report 
the report by the un childrens fund titled children and the 
environment was compiled in association with the un environment 
program and was released on tuesday world environment day 
it listed many of the ills facing children in developing and 
developed countries alike 
forty thousand children under the age of five die daily it said 
about 100 million children live on the streets where they are 
forced to scavenge steal and often fall prey to drugs prostitution 
and gangs it said 
an increasing number of children are aids orphans whose parents 
have died from the dread disease it said 
the number of children living in poverty in the united states has 
risen by more than 3 million over the last 10 years the report said 
despite the discouraging news of poverty sickness and death the 
report said improved international cooperation on the environment 
offers hope as does the thawing of the cold war 
the ending of the cold war provides a unique opportunity for 
the great powers to confront the real threats to planetary 
survival the report said 
sir richard attenborough speaking at a london news conference 
where the report was introduced called on governments and banks in 
developed countries to work together on the third worlds 
appalling debt 
we give less to the third world than we receive ten years ago 
40 billion went from the developed world to developing countries 
now that figure is 60 billion but its going in the opposite 
direction it is a shaming thought said attenborough who 
received an academy award for directing the 1982 film gandhi 
the report emphasized our generations responsibility to 
protect the earth we bequeath our children and suggested that 
priority be given to improving infant mortality rates and education 
in developing countries 
efforts to lower births however well planned cannot fully 
succeed unless they are accompanied by basic programs to protect 
child health and ensure child survival the report said 
