ndic which was proposed in president bushs national drug control 
strategy earlier this year 
several lawmakers questioned the proposal to spend money for the 
center when some law enforcement agencies dont have enough money to 
hire needed agents one congressional aide said later 
there is a general concern that this was not one of the no 1 
priorities that the top priority should be staffing up the law 
enforcement agencies on the street said the staffer who spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
theres still a lot of questions things that are unanswered 
such as how are we going to pay for it another aide said 
the plan outlined in a justice department study calls for no 
money to be spent this fiscal year ending sept 30 however ndic 
would cost about 81 million next year and 459 million in fiscal 
1992 when it would be fully operational with 150 employees 
the first two years include many nonrecurring costs for such 
things as computer equipment so the estimated annual cost after 
that would drop to 267 million the report said 
the study said the money should come from the special forfeiture 
fund in the office of national drug control policy headed by 
william j bennett that money is seized from drug traffickers 
the ndic came in for criticism even before the justice department 
presented its report 
last month three members of the house armed services 
investigations subcommittee said that instead of creating a new 
center the el paso intelligence center in texas should be improved 
that facility run by the drug enforcement administration 
coordinates tactical information to be used immediately such as the 
location of a possibly drugladen aircraft it does not provide 
longrange strategic information 
there is a propensity to proliferate intelligence fusion 
centers as if the administration believed the more intelligence 
centers we created the better intelligence product we would gain 
reps nicholas mavroules dmass lane evans dill and jim 
mccrery rla said in a report but quantity is not quality 
privately some justice department officials agreed but said 
bennetts office had pushed hard for the new intelligence center and 
the proposal reflects a good compromise 
justice department spokeswoman harri j kramer said the need for 
ndic became apparent in the course of involving other 
nontraditional agencies in the drug war such as the defense 
department 
an enhanced mechanism for coordinating interaction between the 
intelligence community and the law enforcement community were also 
needed kramer said the ndic will play an important role in 
addressing these two gaps as well as to refine the process of 
establishing intelligence collection priorities 
bennetts office applauded the justice department proposal it 
is exactly what the president calls for in his drug control 
strategy spokeswoman amy brown said 
ndic will involve the dea fbi immigration and naturalization 
service customs service coast guard cia national security agency 
and the state defense and treasury departments 
