<TEXT>
washington federal safety investigators say thousands of 
bridges need to be inspected by underwater divers to see if they 
face the same danger that caused a tennessee bridge to collapse last 
year killing eight motorists 
the national transportation safety board on tuesday blamed 
erosion from a shifting river channel for the april 1 1989 
collapse of a us 51 bridge over the hatchie river 45 miles north 
of memphis 
it certainly raises a serious concern with me about how much 
damage may have been done with flooding in texas and the south 
said ntsb chairman james kolstad im concerned that some of these 
bridges may be put back into service without adequate inspection 
the board called for a modification of federal bridge inspections 
standards to require underwater inspection of bridge parts exposed 
to excessive water depth or turbidity 
it also asked the tennessee department of transportation to 
follow up bridge inspections with further work by divers when there 
are doubts about submerged elements 
the board cited the 54yearold hatchie bridges simple design as 
a contributing factor in the accident that caused vehicles to plunge 
into the river from the highways two northbound lanes 
a newer southbound span remained intact but board investigators 
said its construction in 1974 accelerated movement of the river 
channel which had changed 83 feet from the time the northbound 
bridge was constructed in 1936 
the board cited the tennessee department of transportation for 
failing to evaluate and correct problems found in inspections dating 
back to 1979 
ntsb investigators said they did not know how many of the 
nations 500000 bridges might require underwater inspection and 
other steps to ensure their safety 
but investigator claude harris said the number needing additional 
scrutiny would number in the thousands 
a survey last year by the national association of counties 
estimated that 165000 bridges need repair or replacement with some 
states having up to 90 percent defective bridges 
the board voted 31 on the probable cause in the tennessee 
collapse and 40 on a set of recommendations to federal and state 
officials board member jim burnett said he would not support the 
conclusion until missing bridge parts are recovered and further 
inspections are made 
the ntsbs investigation remains open said kolstad and could be 
revised if evidence surfaces that points to further deficiencies in 
the bridge investigators told the board that bridge parts might be 
raised from the water in about two weeks 
the board said the bridge failed most likely from the 
deterioration of timber piles that were originally buried and not 
designed to be in water 
board members also cautioned tennessee authorities against 
allowing so many exemptions to vehicle weight restrictions on 
bridges about 70 a month for the hatchie bridge before it 
collapsed and called for closer scrutiny of overweight trucks and 
their impact on bridge safety 
</TEXT>
