<TEXT>
the securities and exchange commission would be 
empowered to curb the practice of program trading during stock 
market emergencies under legislation approved by the house 
the securities markets reform act would allow the sec to limit 
program trading during periods of extraordinary market 
volatility the sharp climbs or drops in stock prices 
the measure introduced last year was adopted by the house on a 
voice vote tuesday 
a similar market reform bill awaiting action by the senate does 
not contain a program trading curb 
critics of program trading rapidfire transactions through 
computerized buy and sell programs blame it for worsening the 1987 
stock market crash and the 190point market slide last oct 13 
they are especially critical of one form of program trading 
index arbitrage in which speculators try to take advantage of 
small brief price differences between the stock and futures markets 
by simultaneously buying large orders in one market while selling 
them in the other 
critics say that strategy and the volatility that often seems to 
accompany it have driven small investors out of the stock market 
last march the treasury department wrote the house energy and 
commerce committee opposing a program trading ban saying the 
measures language was overly broad and potentially harmful to 
market reform 
but the measure was voted out of committee anyway on march 13 
we are not talking about banning computers or legitimate 
program trading strategies far from it said rep edward j 
markey dmass chairman of the finance subcommittee that oversees 
the sec and one of the bills coauthors 
we are giving the sec the tools to protect the securities 
markets from manipulative trading strategies and to prohibit 
trading tactics that threaten fair and orderly markets in times 
of market volatility he said 
in addition to the program trading curb the bipartisan bill 
expands the authority of the sec chairman to shut down the 
securities markets with the presidents permission in times of 
market emergency 
requires large securities traders to report their market 
positions to the sec 
gives the sec authority to assess the financial health of the 
parent holding companies of brokerdealers 
the collapse of drexel burnham lambert inc the onetime junk 
bond giant of wall street was precipitated in february by the 
failure of its parent holding company 
sec chairman richard c breeden has complained that under current 
law the agency did not have adequate information about drexels 
holding company before the firms collapse and that information 
about large stock trades was inadequate for government 
decisionmakers during the oct 13 market slide 
the program trading amendment in the house bill would require the 
sec to determine through its oftenlengthy rulemaking process 
what types of activities cause or contribute to extraordinary 
volatility before it could halt them 
</TEXT>
