the proposal crafted with help from a mediator would have set a 
minimum hauling rate of 35 an hour going up to 40 by january the 
truckers want 40 now 
the independents who pay their own running costs and maintain 
their vehicles are paid 26 to 35 an hour 
earlier tuesday truckers removed their rigs blocking most 
commercial traffic at the border between washington state and 
british columbia the drivers were served with an injunction late 
monday 
the blockades had been in place since thursday at crossings north 
of blaine oroville sumas and lynden in washington and at two 
major canadian highways 
the blockades were the most serious in a series of escalating job 
actions since independent truckers went on strike in late may the 
roadblocks resulted in food and fuel shortages in the province and 
in point roberts a small washington state peninsula accessible 
overland only through british columbia 
