the los angeles county board of supervisors 
will appeal a federal judges ruling that it illegally diluted 
hispanic voting strength in drawing district boundaries in 1981 
the boards conservative majority voted 30 tuesday to continue 
the 2yearold 3 million court battle of the fivemember boards 
two liberal members one dissented but left before the vote and the 
other abstained 
conservative pete schabarum who is retiring accused us 
district judge david kenyon of exerting extraordinary personal 
bias in mondays ruling 
kenyon said the board members conspired to protect their 
incumbencies and that of their allies when they redrew the 
countys voting districts in 1981 
in so doing kenyon added the supervisors violated the 1965 
federal voting rights act and the equal protection clause of the 
14th amendment to the constitution 
a lawsuit filed in 1988 accused the supervisors of deliberately 
spreading the countys hispanic population across several districts 
the plaintiffs included a hispanic organization and the us justice 
department 
hispanics make up about 35 percent of the countys 87 million 
people no hispanic has been elected to the board in more than 100 
years 
kenyon scheduled a conference for thursday to discuss options 
such as ordering an immediate redrawing of district boundaries 
plaintiffs in the lawsuit have said the results of tuesdays 
