<TEXT>
the government today proposed legislation that would 
give france one of the worlds toughest antismoking laws and impose 
a total ban on tobacco ads in 1993 
the bill approved today by the cabinet also would severely 
restrict advertising for alcoholic beverages ads for hard liquor 
would be allowed only in publications geared specifically toward 
adults and must carry a message about the health hazards of drinking 
under the law expected to win easy approval in the national 
assembly cigarette packs will have to carry a health warning and 
smoking will be banned in a wide range of public places 
a separate bill is expected to be introduced soon that would 
raise cigarette prices by 15 percent the biggest single increase 
ever in france the government sets cigarette prices 
100000 people die prematurely in france each year because of 
tobacco and excess alcohol consumption said cabinet spokesman 
louis le pensac this is an intolerable human social and economic 
cost 
under the legislation submitted by health minister claude evin 
all direct and indirect tobacco advertising will be banned as of 
jan 1 1993 including the sponsorship of sports and cultural 
events by tobacco companies 
even the use of cigarette trademarks as logos on nontobacco 
items such as clothing or luggage will be banned le pensac said 
cigarette manufacturers have contended that a ban on tobacco 
advertising would not affect consumption but they estimate the 
proposed price increase will lower sales by 10 percent 
ironically the government is a major producer of cigarettes the 
governments wholly owned tobacco company produces such brands as 
gauloises and gitanes and controls about 51 percent of the cigarette 
market 
