more violence broke out today in a republic of 
soviet central asia where a land dispute between ethnic groups has 
left 40 people dead and more than 200 injured in the past three 
days an official said 
anatoly lukyanov chairman of the supreme soviet legislature 
gave the figures in a report to lawmakers on the latest outbreak of 
ethnic fighting to confront the government of president mikhail s 
gorbachev 
lukyanov did not give a breakdown of the deaths by ethnic groups 
in the republic of kirghizia where fighting began monday between 
kirghiz and uzbeks the tass news agency has said only 32 people 
have died in the clashes and 200 were injured no breakdown was 
given in its report either 
police fired on members of both ethnic groups who tried to storm 
police stations in the city of osh in the densely populated western 
part of the republic near its border with uzbekistan the tass news 
agency said today 
the difficult process of regulating the conflict is going on 
lukyanov told lawmakers he asked deputies from the two republics to 
appeal for calm 
the violence continued for a third day today and the casualties 
included 21 members of law enforcement agencies lukyanov said he 
did not give any further details or say how many of the 21 had been 
killed and how many injured 
he said osh itself was calm but that the violence had moved to 
three other nearby areas outside the city 
ethnic uzbeks from the fergana valley of uzbekistan arrived in 
the area to help their comrades fight lukyanov said adding the 
soviet defense ministry dispatched reinforcements from the republic 
of turkmenia to the osh area 
the clashes spread to the nearby town of uzgen where six of the 
deaths and 18 injuries were reported police in frunze the capital 
of kirghizia were placed on alert 
a duty officer of the osh police said most shops and factories 
reopened today after being shut down on tuesday the officer who 
spoke in a telephone intervew refused to give his name 
