a hydrogen leak that postponed 
columbias astronomy mission reappeared during a test today and 
nasa officials were analyzing the data to pinpoint the source of the 
escaping fuel 
officials hoped to know by late thursday how to repair the leak 
and reschedule columbias mission said george diller spokesman for 
the national aeronautics and space administration 
it seems to be a given now that any time we go into filling the 
tank with hydrogen that the leak will reappear when we reach a 
certain temperature which is approximately minus 420 degrees 
said diller 
the theory was that the leak would only manifest itself in the 
supercold conditions of liquid hydrogen and that has been the 
case he said 
about onesixth of columbias external tank was filled with 
liquid hydrogen traces of the fuel were detected in the aft engine 
compartment 
the leak appears to be in or near a tight cavity between two 
metal plates that connect the orbiter and external tank diller 
said twentyone sensors were placed around the suspected area a 
17inchdiameter valve in a pipe that runs through both plates 
the external tank was drained following the 2hour test 
this test should really point us to it said bascom murrah a 
nasa official in charge of columbias prelaunch operations if we 
dont find it were going to be one unhappy puppy 
nasa officials fear columbia will have to be returned to the 
hangar for repairs which would delay its trip into orbit with the 
150 million astro observatory by about a month 
a launch attempt last week was scrubbed because of a hydrogen 
leak in the engine compartment during fueling with liquid hydrogen 
and liquid oxygen the mission already was two weeks late because of 
cooling system repairs 
workers were cleared from the launch pad during todays hazardous 
test hydrogen is highly combustible 
</TEXT>
