<TEXT>
east german retailers restaurant owners and 
other businessmen today called on their workers to strike next week 
because many will lose their jobs when the german states merge their 
economies next month 
three associations representing thousands of small and 
mediumsized businesses said perhaps half east germanys enterprises 
would be unable to compete under the terms of the economic treaty 
between the germanys 
klaus noack head of the association for independent businesses 
said 350000 workers would lose their jobs this summer and 3 million 
more jobs would be threatened some analysts have put the figure 
even higher 
noack leaders from the chamber of commerce and other business 
groups will call a strike on east germanys baltic sea island of 
reugen tuesday and a nationwide strike the following week unless 
parliament acts on their demands 
we feel that all along we have been abandoned dieter froese 
head of the association for independent businesses said in an 
interview wednesday with the east berlin newspaper berliner zeitung 
the east german newspaper berliner zeitung had reported the city 
strike would be on friday and the nationwide strike on saturday 
however officials later said at a news conference the strikes would 
not be called this week 
the german states are to merge their economies on july 2 when 
east germany will officially become a free market businesses once 
controlled by the former communist government will be free to 
compete but many sell products that are increasingly shunned by 
east germans 
the call to strike came despite the governments announcement a 
day earlier that it will spend 125 billion to retrain workers and 
pay them compensatory wages for lost or reduced salaries 
under the governments program announced tuesday east german 
industries will reduce wages and hours of many workers rather than 
lay them off said labor and social minister regine hildebrandt 
workers will receive compensation payments for time spent 
receiving retraining their reduced wages and the supplemental 
payments combined will likely be lower than their wages but higher 
than jobless benefits said mrs hildebrandt 
government figures released tuesday showed joblessness tripled 
last monthat the end of june 100000 people were officially 
unemployed about 1 percent of the work force but nearly three 
times the 35000 recorded in midapril mrs hildebrandt said 
even though a 1 percent jobless rate is minuscule by western 
standards the speed with which it materialized is alarming in a 
nation where joblessness was once officially nonexistent she said 
she predicted high unemployment in the coming months 
we must build a dam against unemployment said west german 
labor minister norbert bluem in an interview published today in the 
west german newspaper bild 
east germany is to officially shed four decades of socialism on 
july 2 when it merges its economy and social institutions with west 
germany the biggest and most difficult stage of full german 
unification 
officials in both german states are counting on a flood of 
western investment to create new employment 
but many east germans are not waiting to find out west germany 
said tuesday that east germans are still fleeing to west germany at 
a rate of 2000 a week and that more than 180000 have done so this 
year alone 
hundreds of thousands fled last year an exodus that opened the 
berlin wall and helped bring down the former socialist regime in 
october 
western firms already have begun taking over parts of the east 
german economy western food imports for example fill east german 
grocery stores and many east germans have been buying western 
clothing and electronics 
the effect has been to speed the decline of many east german 
industries 
</TEXT>
