<TEXT>
the family of a sailor who drowned during 
a rescue drill is challenging the legal doctrine that bans lawsuits 
against the military for deaths or injuries incident to service 
the us supreme court laid down what is called the feres 
doctrine in 1950 when it refused to let survivors of rudolf j 
feres a soldier killed in a barracks fire sue the government under 
the federal tort claims act 
in action filed monday a lawyer for the family of airman recruit 
lee mirecki urged us district judge winston arnow to overrule the 
feres doctrine claiming it is contrary to the intent of congress as 
well as unfair and irrational 
failing that wrote martin levin arnow should rule the doctrine 
doesnt apply to the mirecki case either because his death at the 
navy rescue swimmer school was not incident to service or because he 
had withdrawn from the navy which he was allowed by contract to do 
by repeatedly shouting i quit as instructors forced him back 
into a training pool 
when the military personnel know or should know that they are 
violating the clear constitutional rights of a serviceman the court 
should rule that the acts are so egregious that it cannot be 
said that the injury resulted incident to service levin wrote 
mirecki 19 of appleton wis died march 2 1988 at the 
pensacola naval air station of drowning and heart failure induced by 
fear a navy pathologist testified during a subsequent court martial 
one instructor was convicted of negligent homicide and sentenced 
to 90 days in the brig a second trial cleared the officer in charge 
of the school of dereliction of duty four other instructors 
received administrative penalties the commander of the naval 
aviation schools command was reprimanded 
mireckis mother elaine m kitowski and the sailors estate are 
seeking 75 million 
the government has asked that the lawsuit be dismissed because of 
the feres doctrine arnow will rule on that motion after the 
government responds to levins argument 
mirecki had signed a statement permitting him to drop on 
request from rescue swimmer school 
</TEXT>
