<TEXT>
groups representing thousands of small east 
german businesses said on wednesday that the terms of german 
unification will force them to lay off 350000 workers this summer 
klaus noack leader of an independent business association said 
half of the nations 500000 small and mediumsized businesses may 
have to declare bankruptcy this year 
noack and two other groups the chamber of commerce and the 
entrepreneurs association said they would call a warning 
strike on the baltic sea island of ruegen on tuesday and a 
nationwide strike the next day unless parliament acted on their 
demands 
the main complaint is a key provision of an economic treaty under 
which east germany and west germany are to merge their economies on 
july 2 the principal stage of full unification 
the treaty which still must be ratified by both parliaments 
calls for east germanys essentially worthless currency to be 
replaced by the powerful west german mark 
workers will have their wages converted to west german marks at 
an equal 11 exchange but business bank accounts will be converted 
at a 21 rate in effect halving their cash reserves in relation to 
their employee payrolls 
noack said that will force perhaps half of the small and 
mediumsized businesses to file for bankruptcy and immediately 
eliminate 350000 jobs 
he claimed the treaty would eventually threaten almost 3 million 
of east germanys 10 million workers 
the business groups said at a news conference that they also need 
the property on which their businesses stand to be protected from 
western investers 
the german governments are still negotiating how to transfer the 
vast publicly owned property in the country to the private sector 
many east germans fear that west germans will buy up their property 
noack said the businesses need their property to use as 
collateral to obtain loans to keep operating and become competitive 
with western firms already selling their products in east germany 
prime minister lothar de maizieres cabinet met on wednesday and 
endorsed a plan to promote small businesses that includes extending 
credit to them said spokesman klauspeter bigalke but he said 
there were no details worked out 
analysts say that between 500000 and 4 million east germans will 
lose their jobs as outmoded overstaffed factories and other 
businesses are forced to compete with western businesses 
east german labor minister regine hildebrandt said wednesday that 
she expected 1 million to lose their jobs 
much of the unemployment is expected to hit the vast industrial 
sector where the huge staterun factories many of which are 
considered environmental hazards are expected to lure little 
private investment or be able to compete with leaner western 
industries 
both german governments are counting on western investment to 
create new jobs in east germany and alleviate the initial effects of 
the countrys move to a free market 
</TEXT>
