<TEXT>
the senate on wednesday endorsed a change in a 
major civil rights bill to allow aids sufferers to be reassigned 
from food handling duties 
the vote was a major electionyear victory for sen jesse helms 
rnc and a setback for majority leader george mitchell helms is 
seeking a fourth term 
on a voice vote the senate approved a nonbinding motion by 
helms to have the americans with disabilities act include an 
exemption that would allow employers to reassign infected workers 
from foodhandling jobs 
helms motion instructs senate negotiators to accept a 
houseadopted exemption when they work out a final version of the 
bill later this month 
sen tom harkin the iowa democrat who sponsored the senate 
measure said the amendment would codify ignorance about the 
disease and how it is transmitted 
the house approved the exemption 199187 last month before it 
finally passed the entire disabilities act 40320 the senate passed 
the bill 768 last september 
the amendment goes right at the heart and soul of the americans 
with disabilities act said harkin to pass legislation in 
spite of the clear and convincing overwhelming medical evidence 
that hiv that aids cannot be transmitted either through air or 
through food is simply to codify ignorance 
but helms renewing the house debate argued that scientific 
knowledge and public perception clash he expressed doubts over the 
certainty of knowledge about how aids is transmitted and argued that 
the amendment was needed because of public ignorance 
weve been told over and over again aids is supposedly not 
communicable by food or drink or casual contact helms said now 
that is the conventional wisdom but you try telling that to john q 
public 
because the helms motion was approved on a voice vote no 
individual senators vote was recorded however the senate voted 
5340 to reject an earlier motion by mitchell a maine democrat to 
table the helms motion 
the house version of the amendment would allow employers to 
reassign hivinfected workers from foodhandling jobs provided 
other positions exist for which they are qualified opponents say 
that means infected people could be fired or demoted 
the house adopted the amendment even though health and human 
services secretary louis w sullivan said it was unnecessary the 
white house has not however spoken out against the amendment 
although it specifically endorsed another unrelated change 
the house amendment was introduced by rep jim chapman dtexas 
it was endorsed by the restaurant and foodservice industry as 
well as by the national federation of independent business a chief 
critic of the entire disabilities bill 
were enormously disappointed at the senate vote today and view 
