<TEXT>
the superpowers could cut their arsenals of 
longrange nuclear weapons by three times the amount planned in a 
nearly completed treaty without endangering security us and 
soviet scientists said wednesday 
the groups said in a jointly published book that the united 
states and the soviet union could reduce the number of strategic 
nuclear warheads to fewer than 2000 each without giving either side 
an incentive to launch a first strike 
in the strategic arms reduction talks in geneva us and soviet 
negotiators are trying to complete a start treaty to reduce to 6000 
the number of warheads on weapons capable of reaching each others 
territory that would represent about a 30 percent cut from current 
levels 
at last weeks summit meeting in washington president bush and 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev reaffirmed their commitment to 
completing the start treaty and agreed to pursue negotiations on 
further reductions once the treaty is signed and ratified 
the federation of american scientists and the committee of soviet 
scientists for global security proposed a new way of structuring 
arms reduction treaties 
it would be based on eliminating warheads not just the vehicles 
such as bombers ballistic missiles or missile launchers that carry 
the warheads to targets 
the start treaty as drafted includes no prohibitions against 
removing warheads from longrange missiles and converting them for 
use on other weapons both the american and soviet governments say 
dismantlement of warheads would give away vital secret information 
about the design of their weapons 
the scientists also said that for warhead dismantlement to be 
effective the superpowers should agree also to halt production of 
new fissionable materials including plutonium and enriched uranium 
used in warheads 
there is growing congressional interest in pursuing a ussoviet 
agreement to halt nuclear materials production but the bush 
administration is opposed 
the scientists noted that both moscow and washington already have 
been forced to reduce their nuclear materials production because of 
safety problems in manufacturing 
just this week new evidence emerged to indicate that problems at 
a key us weapons plant are more serious that previously believed 
a panel of nuclear safety experts commissioned by the energy 
department to advise energy secretary james d watkins on weapons 
production facilities said tuesday that plans for resuming plutonium 
processing at the rocky flats plant in colorado should be further 
delayed to correct numerous training and pollution problems 
rocky flats the nations only supplier of plutonium triggers for 
nuclear warheads was closed indefinitely in november because of 
safety and management concerns 
watkins had indicated recently that he hoped to restart rocky 
flats this month and that its operation was vital to maintaining the 
nations nuclear weapons stockpile 
he had no immediate comment on the advisory panels 
recommendation 
in a related development the author of a new report by the 
private arms control association in washington told reporters that 
congress was likely to slash 1991 spending for the star wars 
antimissile defense by more than 20 percent from 1990 levels 
matthew bunn an arms control specialist said it was likely 
congress would approve about 3 billion in spending for star wars 
officially the strategic defense initiative for the budget year 
beginning oct 1 
the current budget is 38 billion and the bush administration 
wants 48 billion for 1991 
</TEXT>
