federal regulators assured members of congress 
wednesday that a government crackdown on bank lending is not the 
cause of a credit squeeze in some regions 
behind closed doors however bankers are pleading with the 
regulators to ease up 
senior federal banking officials appearing before the house 
small business committee conceded that some banks are making it 
more difficult for businesses to get loans particularly for 
commercial real estate projects 
but they said that is mostly a justified response to a sluggish 
economy rather than a reaction to intensified scrutiny from 
government examiners 
meanwhile chief executives of some of the nations largest banks 
have asked the federal reserve board to bend capital standards while 
they work off losses from sour real estate loans 
the request came from the feds 12member advisory council at a 
private may 3 meeting in washington the central bank keeps the 
minutes of the councils sessions secret for three years but a copy 
from last months meeting was obtained by the associated press 
the council suggested that regulators should permit banks to 
deduct real estate loan losses from their earnings over a period of 
years rather than all at once they also asked for relaxed capital 
rules to permit banks to hold on to repossessed real estate rather 
than selling it in a depressed market 
such accounting measures while maintaining the appearance of 
balanced books have been blamed for contributing to the savings and 
loan crisis 
the councils request to the fed for lenience was originally 
disclosed in wednesday editions of usa today 
regulators told the small business panel chaired by rep john j 
lafalce dny that they have cautioned their examiners not to be 
overzealous in scrutinizing loans 
but for the most part they stood firm in the face of strong 
congressional criticism that creditworthy constituents were having 
trouble getting loans 
