<TEXT>
a top soviet trade official made it clear 
wednesday that once the ussoviet trade agreement wins final 
approval in congress his country will be looking for us loans to 
help the troubled soviet economy 
yuri n chumakov deputy minister of foreign economic relations 
said west european countries and canada already were offering such 
loans and loan guarantees to make sales in the soviet union the 
government of president mikhail gorbachev would expect the same from 
the united states he said 
the united states is our greatest food supplier we have been 
paying with cash chumakov told a gathering of us businessmen 
we have the right to expect in this hard period to receive certain 
credits in order to withstand the pressure 
chumakovs remarks referred to the turmoil facing the soviet 
economy which is plagued by food shortages sagging production and 
inflation as it attempts to move from a centrally planned system to 
one based on free markets 
the united states currently is blocked from extending loan relief 
to the soviets by the same law which keeps tariffs at high levels on 
soviet exports to this country 
the 1974 jacksonvanik provision says the soviets cannot qualify 
for the most favorable tariffs or for us government loans until a 
trade agreement is completed and the president certifies that the 
soviet union allows free emigration 
bush has said he will send the trade agreement to congress along 
with a presidential request for favored trade status once the soviet 
legislature passes an emigration measure now expected this fall 
under the jacksonvanik provision if congress agrees with the 
presidents recommendations it would clear the way for millions of 
dollars in credit from us agencies which promote export sales by 
american farmers and corporations 
the agencies involved include the exportimport bank which deals 
with sales of us industrial products and the commodity credit 
corporation which promotes us farm sales 
chumakovs appearance before of a group of us corporate 
officials interested in doing business in the soviet union was part 
of an orchestrated effort on the part of the soviets to attract 
western investment and technology chumakov was the leader of the 
soviet team which negotiated the new trade agreement 
asked if he thought it was realistic to be seeking additional 
loans from the west at a time when the soviets are falling behind in 
repaying loans they have already received chumakov replied one 
seeks credit not when he is welloff but when he is on hard times 
chumakov predicted gorbachevs perestroika program for reforming 
the soviet economy would succeed although he conceded we have 
already had a few mistakes in implementation these are 
inevitable 
chumakov said there was no ulterior motive in the decision by the 
supreme soviet to put off until the fall consideration of a law 
liberalizing emigration policies saying it had fallen victim to 
time constraints caused by the need to consider emergency economic 
legislation 
the delay was seen by the bush administration as a plus giving 
gorbachev more time to craft a compromise on the question of 
lithuanian independence an issue that threatens congressional 
approval of the trade pact 
chumakov called the trade agreement a critical first step to 
ending nearly 50 years of commercial cold war between the two 
nations he said it would lead to expanded opportunities in a number 
of areas including space telecommunications and aviation 
he suggested that american companies should consider a soviet 
offer to launch us commercial satellites on soviet rockets 
we have a lot of rockets free now from military applications 
he said why should we throw them away and lose money on them 
