<TEXT>
president fw de klerk is 
likely to lift the 4yearold state of emergency on thursday 
according to a report by the independent south african press 
association 
the news agency in a report wednesday that did not cite sources 
said de klerk was expected to announce his plans when he addresses 
parliament in cape town on thursday afternoon 
if de klerk ends the emergency it would remove a major obstacle 
to blackwhite negotiations on a new constitution de klerk says he 
wants the document to allow the countrys 28 million blacks to share 
power with the 5 million whites 
presidential spokesman kobie pieterse said the report by the 
south african press association was purely speculation he 
confirmed de klerk was to make a previously unannounced speech to 
parliament but declined to divulge the contents 
the african national congress and other leading antiapartheid 
groups have said the repeal of the emergency is a precondition for 
fullscale negotiations 
the emergency laws which include some of the harshest measures 
ever imposed by south africas white rulers must be renewed by 
midnight friday if they are to remain in effect 
de klerk met wednesday with his cabinet and they were expected 
to make a final decision on whether to lift or extend the emergency 
pieterse declined to discuss details of the cabinet talks 
de klerk has eased some of the emergency rules but among those 
remaining in effect are that police can detain people without charge 
indefinitely 
police also can still declare an unrest area and order all 
people including journalists to leave they can conduct searches 
and seize materials without a warrant and they cannot be prosecuted 
for their actions under the emergency if they act in good faith 
de klerk has said he wants to lift the emergency but will not do 
so until authorities are confident they can control violence that 
claimed more than 500 black lives in the first three months of this 
year 
leading newspapers and political analysts have been virtually 
unanimous in predicting the relaxation or lifting of emergency rules 
i only hope that the government will see the necessity of 
lifting the state of emergency anc leader nelson mandela said 
last week before departing on a sixweek tour of europe north 
america and africa it has been absolutely ineffective 
the wideranging emergency rules initially banned most forms of 
peaceful protest and made it illegal to call for boycotts or foreign 
sanctions to seek to undermine the security forces or to report on 
police actions or unrest without permission 
more than 30000 activists almost all of them black have been 
detained without trial for varying lengths of time during the 
emergency others went into hiding 
dozens of opposition groups were banned and several 
antiapartheid newspapers were shut down temporarily police 
repeatedly raided black trade union offices and broke up political 
meetings and demonstrations in black townships and on university 
campuses 
de klerk has nullified some of the restrictions as part of a 
series of reforms implemented since he assumed power last august he 
also has released scores of detainees and longterm political 
prisoners 
about 300 activists currently are in jail under the emergency 
regulations according to the human rights commission a private 
group 
an estimated 6000 blacks have died in the past four years most 
of them in blackonblack violence in the southeastern province of 
natal but scores have been killed in clashes with police including 
more than 30 deaths in recent months 
existing security laws permit detention without trial allow the 
government to place people under tight restrictions such as house 
arrest and provide authority to ban peaceful meetings and 
demonstrations 
de klerks predecessor pw botha declared the nationwide 
emergency june 12 1986 in a bid to quell mounting black unrest 
the action unleashed a storm of protest both inside south africa 
and abroad the south african currency fell sharply foreign 
investors grew nervous and many subsequently withdrew also efforts 
to impose economic sanctions against south africa gained momentum 
</TEXT>
