<TEXT>
a new policy halting the explusion of some 
palestinians in the occupied lands affects thousands who have been 
separated from their families a civil rights group said wednesday 
under the government decision announced tuesday wives and 
children of palestinians who live in west bank or gaza strip without 
residency permits would be allowed to live in the occupied 
territories unless there is a specific negative security reason 
to deny the request 
the decision came after israels association for civil rights 
appealed the expulsions of 15 palestinians and after us criticism 
that expelling women and children without such permits was dividing 
arab families 
the new regulations say arabs in the occupied west bank and gaza 
strip will be allowed to ask for residency status for members of 
their families who can remain as visitors 
netta goldman a lawyer with the association for civil rights 
said the group also won a court order specifying that as visitors 
wives and children would be entitled to normal health benefits and 
schooling 
this affects thousands and thousands of people she said 
under past regulations only palestinians who lived in the 
occupied lands during a september 1967 census were automatically 
eligible for residency permits 
that did not include thousands of palestinian women whose 
families fled to jordan when israel seized the west bank and gaza in 
the june 1967 mideast war and who later married men from the 
occupied areas 
wives and children denied residency permits would enter the 
occupied lands on threemonth guest visas then had to abandon their 
families and return to jordan for several months or stay illegally 
according to the army 251 palestinians including 88 women and 
78 children were expelled from the territories last year because 
they lacked residency permits the army has no figures for preceding 
years 
in january the us state department questioned the expulsion 
practices defense minister yitzhak rabin immediately ordered a 
temporary halt to the practice and promised to review it 
according to rabin 88249 requests for family reunification have 
been received since 1967 and 13509 of those were granted 
palestinians activists have claimed the expulsions were part of a 
strategy to force palestinians out of the occupied lands but 
israeli officials denied this 
still the issue has been seen as part of a demographic war with 
some palestinians trying to increase their numbers in the 
territories while israel tried to limit the growth about 17 
million arabs and 70000 jews live in the occupied lands 
palestinian activist and lawyer jonathan kuttab said wednesday 
the new rules were a positive thing but would still leave tens 
of thousands of palestinians as exiles 
he said the decision was an attempt to reduce the damage from 
the glaring discrimination of allowing total strangers like 
soviet jews to come here while denying the basic rights of 
palestinians who have family and roots here to come back to their 
land 
