<TEXT>
a private project to improve rural 
americans cardiovascular health resulted in an average ninepound 
loss of body fat as well as reduced cholesterol and blood pressure 
organizers said wednesday 
were talking about an impressive improvement in the quality of 
life about people being more productive and less stressed said 
bill reger director of bayer cos 33 million twoyear study 
our success has been phenomenal 
participants were encouraged to follow a lowfat highfiber 
diet to exercise and to use stress management techniques 
free cooking and aerobics classes were offered along with 
lectures on heart disease nutrition and weight loss stopsmoking 
clinics also were available 
those in the study which began in may 1988 had their blood 
pressures cholesterol pulse rates and other factors checked every 
three months 
the programs final screenings were completed late last month 
results from that screening will be distributed to the participants 
beginning thursday 
the program one of the first privately funded public health 
education programs for rural areas was sponsored by bayer and its 
new yorkbased parent company glenbrook laboratories 
organizers chose wellsburg a town of about 4000 people about 
45 miles southwest of pittsburgh because of its small population 
the 517 people who went through the program from start to finish 
lost an average of 86 pounds of body fat reger said an average 
52 pounds of that fat was converted to muscle tissue resulting in 
an average weight loss of 36 pounds 
the participants also saw their cholesterol reduced from an 
average reading of 220 at the start of the study to 208 
the reduction may not seem to be that much at first blush 
said reger but if you look further the people at the most risk 
were the ones who made the greatest positive changes and were 
thrilled with that 
average blood pressures of those in the study dropped from an 
average 132 over 81 to 126 over 78 
again the changes may appear modest but the people at most 
risk had the biggest reductions said reger overall people in 
the program are using far fewer high blood pressure medications now 
than they were two years ago 
west virginia has one of the highest obesity rates in the country 
at 29 percent according to a 1988 report by the federal centers for 
disease control the same study found that 27 percent of west 
virginians smoked 
nearly everyone in the study reported reducing their salt and fat 
intake and 57 percent of those who smoked when they started the 
program have quit reger said 
</TEXT>
