<TEXT>
the us justice department was 
considering its next move wednesday after a federal judge threw out 
a desegregation lawsuit against the charleston county school 
district 
us district judge sol blatt jr late tuesday dismissed the 1981 
lawsuit which challenged a 1967 law creating the nearly 
43000student countywide school district 
in another decadesold desegregation battle school officials in 
jacksonville fla and naacp leaders agreed on a countywide 
desegregation plan with reduced mandatory busing 
in the south carolina case blatt found no intent to discriminate 
by state lawmakers who passed the 1967 law he ruled that some 
schools in the district remain predominantly black because of the 
makeup of neighborhoods geography and decisions by white parents to 
put their students in private schools 
justice department spokeswoman amy casner said the department was 
reviewing the decision and had not decided whether to appeal notice 
of appeal must generally be made within 60 days she said in a 
telephone interview from washington 
the 1967 act created a countywide school board to oversee eight 
local school districts and spread tax money among them the local 
boards retained control of faculty and student assignments however 
making it slightly more difficult to achieve greater 
desegregation blatt found 
the justice department later joined by the naacp legal defense 
and education fund asked that the local districts be abolished and 
blatt order a better integration plan 
fiftysix percent of the districts 42774 students are black 35 
percent of the black students attend classes in schools that are 90 
percent black but blatt said this was not necessarily evidence of 
illegal segregation 
it is possible that even without the local districts true 
integration would be impossible in charleston county because of its 
rather unique geography the judge wrote 
with all of its rivers and bridges and its nearly 100mile 
area extensive busing would be extremely dangerous he said 
blatts decision followed years of delays in the case and 11 
months of arguments in a nonjury trial involving 80 witnesses and 
more than 2600 exhibits 
arthur mcfarland an attorney representing student plaintiffs in 
the case said the decision will have to be reviewed before an 
appeal is considered 
in jacksonville the duval county school board and us district 
judge john h moore ii must approve the agreement school officials 
reached with the local chapter of the national association for the 
advancement of colored people 
it would eliminate the busing of some 14000 students change 
groupings of grade levels provide 60 million for innercity school 
improvements and set up programs to attract students of all races to 
schools that have predominantly black enrollments 
superintendent larry zenke called the agreement reached tuesday 
after almost six months of negotiations a winwin proposition 
for both sides 
the rev henry green president of a coalition of about 60 black 
ministers said black residents must take a waitandsee attitude 
to make sure that promises that have been made are kept because so 
many promises that have been made in the past have been broken 
duval county was ordered by a federal judge in the early 1960s to 
desegregate its schools courtordered crosstown busing began in 
1971 and the naacp sued again in 1985 claiming the school system 
was not fully desegregated 
moore ruled in 1988 that students in duval county were getting an 
equal education but last fall an appeals court disagreed and placed 
the school system back under court review leading to the recent 
negotiations 
