<TEXT>
as a lesson in capitalism us policy on trade 
with moscow loses something in the translation in this case 
business doesnt come before pressure 
commercial decisions hinge on soviet behavior and on american 
politics not on the marketplace 
and consistency is not part of the package 
pressing soviet trade the old communist mikhail s gorbachev 
argued like a businessman the course that now suits his economic 
purpose he told political leaders in washington and business 
leaders in minneapolis and san francisco that if american traders 
and investors dont move quickly into newly opening soviet markets 
other interests will be there first 
that concerns administration officials but they also have to 
deal with political realities one of which is that congress will 
not agree to a new trade deal until moscow offers at least a gesture 
toward granting lithuania independence 
the trade agreement gorbachev took home from the summit was 
described by the white house as a symbol of support for soviet 
economic change but it is only a symbol it will not be completed 
any time soon 
the soviet parliament may put off until fall its final action on 
an emigration law president bush said must be enacted before he 
sends the trade deal to congress even when that step is taken the 
agreement is not going anywhere without some easing in gorbachevs 
economic crackdown on lithuania 
at same time a renewed grain sales agreement is taking effect 
without regard to kremlin behavior on lithuanias independence drive 
or anything else 
the fiveyear grain deal extends agreements dating from 1976 
us negotiators wanted that one it is an economic boon to the 
midwest it expands the business american farmers already are doing 
and putting it in any doubt would be politically perilous 
when thenpresident carter imposed a partial grain embargo in 
1980 to punish the soviet union for the invasion of afghanistan 
republicans denounced the step 
they said wheat should not have been made a diplomatic weapon 
argued that moscow would simply buy its grain elsewhere ronald 
reagan lifted the embargo shortly after he became president 
the trade agreement and the mostfavorednation tariff status 
gorbachev wants are new business and politically vulnerable with 
no domestic constituency involved the grain sales are big business 
with powerful us voting interests behind them soviet negotiators 
apparently didnt want to sign the grain deal unless the trade deal 
also was signed 
grain sales including wheat sold at subsidized prices account 
for most current us trade with the soviet union under the new 
agreement those sales are supposed to increase to 6 to 8 billion a 
year 
soviet exports to the united states did not reach 1 billion last 
year 
the trade agreement could open the path to greatly expanded 
commerce between the two powers although at this point the soviet 
union does not have much to sell its major us exports now are 
vodka caviar and furs all subject to steep tariffs that would be 
sharply reduced by mostfavorednation treatment 
the trade deal also would make it easier for us companies that 
want to do business in the soviet union 
gorbachevs bottom line was a businessmans theres money to be 
made and the people who get there first will do best 
we need some economic moves some economic steps now he said 
during the summit visit if america lags behind then others come 
in we want america to be in 
he argued his case for the trade deal to congressional leaders 
and in his summit sessions with bush who finally offered the 
gesture of a conditional agreement congressional critics called it 
a cavein on lithuania the senate had voted 7324 on may 1 for a 
resolution saying that there should be no trade agreement without an 
end to the economic crackdown on lithuania 
sen george j mitchell dmaine the majority leader said 
monday that bush clearly expected congress to do what he wouldnt 
do and tie trade to soviet moves toward lithuanian independence 
not only to free emigration the latter condition dates from 1974 
it was set by congress to press for emigration rights for soviet 
jews 
bush also faces a trade policy dispute over his renewal of 
favorable tariff terms for china despite its repression of democracy 
demonstrators and the killings in tiananmen square a year ago 
congressional critics are trying to block the extension but they 
probably lack the votes 
bush had said his action on china sent no message except that 
isolation is bad and economic development is good 
the us message on soviet trade terms isnt quite the same 
