<TEXT>
in these riskaverse times many savers and 
investors are shopping for more than just high yields when they look 
for moneymarket investments 
by all the evidence they are paying extra attention these days 
to the fine distinctions among competing alternatives like treasury 
bills bank certificates of deposit and moneymarket mutual funds 
each of these popular savings vehicles enjoys a longstanding 
reputation for safety and nothing has happened lately to alter that 
description in any drastic way 
nevertheless many financial analysts say the relative merits of 
each species are getting a new appraisal these days in the wake of 
such developments as the government bailout of failed savings 
institutions and a general post1980s tightening of credit standards 
there is a flight to quality from bank cds and commercial paper 
shortterm debt issued by corporations into treasury bills says 
the savings newsletter 100 highest yields 
tbills which are sold by the federal government in threemonth 
sixmonth and oneyear maturities are widely considered to rank 
among the safest paper investments available anywhere in the world 
most bank cds also are governmentbacked in the form of deposit 
insurance of up to 100000 however the sampl crisis has prompted a 
debate over how far uncle sam can and ought to go in the future in 
standing behind the banking system 
investors in money funds have no direct government protection 
but the funds can strive for safety through diversification of their 
portfolios and sticking with securities of toprated borrowers 
including the treasury they also rank high in liquidity and 
convenience 
money funds have come under increased scrutiny in the past year 
however from both regulators and private commentators because of 
defaults by a couple of issuers of commercial paper 
in those instances sponsors of several money funds dug into 
their own pockets to make up for losses that would have at least 
marginally and temporarily reduced the funds yields 
this spring has brought a pause in what was a steady advance of 
moneyfund assets to record highs in april according to the 
investment company institute the total in shortterm mutual funds 
dropped to 4592 billion from 4636 billion the month before 
while payments of income taxes were partly responsible said 
jacob dreyer chief economist at the trade group he also said 
investors purchased large amounts of newly offered treasury bills 
and notes by drawing on their money market fund balances 
if this shift was inspired first of all by a safetyfirst 
philosophy it drew further encouragement from an unusual pattern in 
market rates yields on tbills which typically stand slightly 
lower than the competition right now are very competitive 
as of early this month listings in barrons magazine showed the 
yield on 26week treasury bills at 817 percent compared to 
sixmonth cds at an average of 775 percent and money market funds 
at an average of 768 percent 
it appears analysts say that banks and money funds have made 
some concessions toward safety in their usual competitive efforts to 
offer top yields 
whether of their own volition or in response to regulatory 
prodding they have tightened the standards they apply to the credit 
risks they are willing to take that generally means accepting a 
lower yield 
in addition tbill yields are not affected by the management and 
operating costs that take a slice out of the returns banks and money 
funds can offer 
savers and investors who buy tbills from a bank or broker may 
see their effective returns reduced by transaction charges or 
custodial fees new treasury securities can be bought with no such 
charges however by dealing directly with a federal reserve bank or 
branch 
</TEXT>
