<TEXT>
teachers at rosman elementary school had a 
bold plan to transform their school into a highly unusual learning 
center where parents and students could study side by side 
such a center they believed might help break the cycle of 
poverty and illiteracy in their appalachian community 
but like many good ideas it lacked an essential ingredient 
money 
thats changed since the tiny school became one of 15 across the 
nation awarded grants from the rjr nabisco foundations 30 million 
next century schools program the largest corporate educational 
grant program ever for the benefit of elementary and secondary 
schools 
rosman elementary with 364 students in grades k6 will receive 
750000 over the next three years as part of the tobacco and food 
giants program designed to promote daring even risky changes in 
education 
the rjr grant program was announced last year and winning 
schools got their first awards in april 
its a dream come true said exie henson who teaches second 
and third grade at rosman elementary 
the grant will be used to broaden the mission of the school to 
help kids by helping their parents many of whom have severe social 
economic and educational problems of their own 
thirtysix percent of our kids are considered highrisk said 
principal dawson hogsed and so many of them have parents who also 
dropped out 
the school will transform itself into a parentchild learning 
