many real estate and building people feel a new 
scourge has been let loose upon the american economy regulators 
those regulators they feel are sometimes overzealous 
irritating intimidating and arbitrary and they wonder occasionally 
if the activities of regulators might not even tip the economy into 
recession 
while that possibility might seem farfetched at this point 
david seiders chief economist of the national association of home 
builders asks that very question in an analysis for an association 
publication 
and alan greenspan chairman of the federal reserve board 
pointedly has suggested to bankers that they remain prudent rather 
than reactionary 
many of the real estatebuilding critics now concede that there 
might not be a traditional credit crunch that the federal reserve 
might be right in saying there is enough money out there but they 
add a big but 
the big but is this isnt it the same thing as a credit 
crunch if the banks have the money and because of more critical 
supervision by regulatory officials or their own lending officers 
they are unwilling to lend it 
seiders says there is indeed a crunch a regulatory credit 
crunch 
on feb 8 for example the office of the comptroller of the 
currency or occ issued an advisory letter to chiefs and directors 
of all national banks entitled real estate project and development 
lending 
this letter cited fundamental deficiencies and negative 
trends in bank real estate lending during 1989 and warned about 
problems of loan underwriting appraisal practices and inadequate 
risk analysis 
the result says seiders was to throw a deep chill over the 
source of credit that we were counting on to help fill in for the 
thrifts which of course have their own regulatory and lending 
problems 
all of a sudden he says builders and developers from markets as 
diverse as new england virginia and california reported that banks 
have simply closed their real estate lending windows 
seiders says the banks explain that armies of supervisors have 
them so uptight that real estate lending is just not worth the pain 
