politician wooing the wealthy but forgetting the poor elderly and 
average working south carolinian 
ill be a citizens politician not a career politician 
passailaigue says referring to campbells six years in the general 
assembly and eight years in the us house before becoming governor 
mitchell who is hoping to become the states first black 
governor calls campbell the worst governor of south carolina in 
the 20th century he said campbell catered to the wealthy and 
privileged at the expense of the working people the poor people 
the retired and elderly 
its the oldest trick in the democratic bag of tricks to accuse 
the republicans of wooing the wealthy responded campbell 
spokesman tucker eskew 
the governor kicked off his reelection campaign last month 
stressing gains in the states economy environment and education 
system during his first term 
there is better education there are more jobs and there is a 
safer environment than we had three years ago he said 
his supporters cite the states rising per capita income 4 
percent unemployment rate and campbell initiatives against drugs and 
infant mortality 
campbells political strength is evident in his strong advantage 
in fundraising he has raised about 15 million in comparison with 
mitchells 65000 and passailaigues 69000 
the governor pulled in more than 500000 at a single fundraiser 
attended by president bush in may 
both passailaigue and mitchell have shied away from attacking 
each other a tactic passailaigue says is geared toward a democratic 
victory in november 
i think to beat campbell you have to run the perfect race he 
said you dont have any margin for error 
you really need a unified democratic party and then you need 
those coalitions that the democratic party one time had but no 
longer enjoys including groups such as environmentalists and the 
working class 
the platforms of both men are designed to rebuild those 
coalitions 
mitchell a 51yearold lawyer has consistently pushed for 
greater support of public transportation and assistance to the poor 
he has served in the general assembly for 16 years 
some state democrats privately fear a primary victory for 
mitchell could hasten the departure of whites from the party and 
undercut other democrats on the general election ballot but 
mitchell rejects such talk saying the vast majority of south 
carolinians are more concerned about a persons leadership ability 
experience and vision than his color 
passailaigue a 42yearold certified public accountant was 
first elected to the state senate in 1988 despite his freshman 
status he has been a frequent challenger of the senate leadership 
pushing for consideration of pet projects such as tax reform 
mitchell stresses his own public experience over that of 
passailaigue who responds that there are more important things to 
consider 
i think somebodys vision and what they want to do is more 
important than sitting in the general assembly or holding some other 
elected office passailaigue said 
both democrats say they want to reform the state tax system 
though they advocate different approaches on other issues the 
candidates share similar views 
both support a womans right to an abortion favor a state 
lottery to raise money for education and reject the states status 
as a dump for infectious hazardous and nuclear waste 
mitchell has kept a low public profile during much of the 
campaign but recently accused passailaigue of latching on to his 
own campaign themes 
my opponent has not only adopted my issues but five of my 
phrases as well he said mitchell accused passailaigue of picking 
up phrases of his such as clean nonpolluting industries and 
the regressive tax structure of south carolina 
passailaigue rejected the copycat charge 
</TEXT>
