<DOCNO> AP900606-0252 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a bush administration plan to transfer 
authority over stock index futures from the commodity futures 
trading commission to the rival securities and exchange commission 
could tie up needed legislative reforms for both agencies say 
officials 
the treasury department unveiled the measure tuesday almost a 
month after indicating it would propose legislation to end the turf 
battle between the futures market overseer and the stock market 
regulator 
the cftc and the sec have been locked in an escalating war of 
words over which should oversee financial products that have 
elements of both a security and a futures contract such hybrid 
products include stock index futures which allow investors to 
speculate on movements in the stock market without having to buy the 
underlying stocks 
the administrations bill would unify regulation under the sec 
of the one market of stocks stock options and stock index 
futures according to a treasury fact sheet 
but in a speech delivered earlier tuesday mary l schapiro an 
sec commissioner worried that the bill had slim prospects for 
passage in the dwindling congressional session because this is a 
highly divisive emotionally charged issue on capitol hill 
and while we wallow in the jurisdictional quagmire other 
critically important legislation may be held up ms schapiro told 
the national economists club she favors an outright merger of the 
sec and cftc 
the chairman of the house agriculture committee rep kika de la 
garza dtexas said switching authority from one agency to another 
is not a solution 
the courts have interpreted the commodity exchange act as giving 
the cftc regulatory authority over any financial product with even 
the slightest aspect of a futures contract 
but sec and treasury officials have complained that this has led 
to long and costly legal battles while innovative financial products 
are being developed or copied in overseas markets hurting american 
competitiveness 
the administration bill would modify the exclusivity clause 
of the commodity exchange act to give the sec authority over stock 
index futures 
the move has been opposed vehemently by the cftc and its 
supporters on capitol hill mostly on the agriculture committees of 
the house and senate 
they have claimed that giving stock index futures to the sec will 
hobble the cftcs ability to regulate other futures contracts and 
reduce liquidity in the markets 
de la garza asked the treasury to submit legislative proposals 
to improve cftcs regulation of the markets for stock index 
futures 
noting that a cftc reform bill has been passed in the house but 
remains tied up in committee in the senate over the stock index 
futures issue de la garza called on the senate to act on the cftc 
reauthorization bill at the earlist possible time so we can go to 
conference and produce a final bill that gives the cftc the powers 
that it needs 
in proposing the bill treasury officials maintained tuesday that 
the only real change would be the name of the regulator because 
stock index futures would be regulated under the basic structure 
of the commodity exchange act not as securities 
the administration claimed the disruption to the futures markets 
would be minimal because stock index futures represent less than 
10 percent of the futures volume under cftc jurisdiction 
the bill also would give authority for setting margins the 
downpayment investors must make when buying securities on credit 
on stock index futures to the sec 
currently margins on futures contracts are set by the exchanges 
themselves usually at a fraction of the 50 percent required in 
securities transactions stock market margins are set by the federal 
reserve board the fed favors placing marginsetting authority under 
one agency although it hasnt said which agency it favors 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

