all but one of the sakowitz specialty stores were 
slated for liquidation after no bids were received for the 
texasbased retailer at a bankruptcy court hearing wednesday 
the onceproud chain which includes four stores in houston one 
in dallas and another in cincinnati is 80 percent owned by lj 
hooker corp hooker has been disposing of its assets under 
bankruptcy court supervision 
us bankruptcy court judge tina brozman indicated she would 
approve the plan to liquidate all of the texas sakowitz stores and a 
formal order was expected to be issued soon goingoutofbusiness 
sales would start soon thereafter and run through the end of july 
the sakowitz in cincinnatis forest fair mall would remain open 
business at the shopping mall another hooker holding could suffer 
if the store closed similar arrangements were made when hooker 
divested its bonwit teller and b altman amp co department store 
chains hooker has kept the altmans and bonwit teller stores open 
for business at the forest fair mall hooker also has continued 
operating a bonwit teller in a columbia sc mall that it owns 
the sakowitz chain headquartered in houston has about 450 
employees it has focused on womens apparel and accessories during 
much of its 88 years in business the chain enjoyed a good 
reputation for quality and fashion sense 
but in the mid1980s a struggling regional economy due largely to 
the oil price slump proved too much for sakowitz it entered 
bankruptcy court proceedings in 1985 
sakowitz reorganized in chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code 
and emerged from court protection under the stewardship of a new 
company that teamed up with hooker at that time hooker acquired 
its 80 percent stake 
an attorney for hooker sheldon i hirshon said at the hearing 
that sakowitz never succeeded in really turning itself around in 
the year ended jan 31 1990 sakowitz suffered a net operating loss 
of 44 million and lost 13 million in the past three months 
hirshon said 
at the hearing hooker invited bids for either its interest in 
sakowitz or the assets of the chain no bidders came forward 
an attorney for robert t sakowitz formerly president and chief 
executive officer of the chain told the court that sakowitz had 
wanted to make an offer but needed more time to arrange financing 
sakowitz didnt make a formal bid and judge brozman moved the case 
forward 
sakowitz who attended the hearing and spoke with reporters 
expressed regret at the chains fate and disputed the implication 
that it was beyond redemption 
he distributed a personal statement in which he said the 
complications of hookers bankruptcy proceedings discouraged many 
