<TEXT>
agriculture secretary clayton yeutter warned 
wednesday that an agricultural trade war could result if a deadlock 
over the united states demands at international trade talks 
continues through the end of the year 
the united states is seeking the removal of european farm export 
subsidies over 10 years 
if no agreement is reached i guarantee you the costs for some 
of our trading partners would increase dramatically said yeutter 
the luncheon speaker at a forum sponsored by the journal of commerce 
and the national foreign trade council 
the united states has to protect its own interests yeutter 
said ive thought about how we can do that and hope i can keep 
those thoughts in the back of my mind and never have to surface 
them 
yeutter while conceding that us farm policies also distort 
trade said us export subsidies amount to less than 1 billion a 
year while european help for farm exports comes to 10 billion 
annually 
we all have to go down the reform road together yeutter said 
yeutter said proposals for cutting european subsidies in half are 
insufficient 
the common markets export subsidies are intended to help 
relatively expensive european farm products compete against 
lowerpriced goods in the world market 
us negotiators unsuccessfully pushed their call to stop export 
subsidies as well as an end to import barriers and domestic 
subsidies at a meeting of the organization for economic cooperation 
and development last week in paris 
i am never surprised about intransigence on the part of the 
european community yeutter said of the deadlock 
us trade representative carla hills and other officials have 
said the agricultural issue is the linchpin for all other topics 
in the current round of negotiations under the general agreement on 
tariffs and trade or gatt a forum for promoting freer trade 
the talks known as the uruguay round began in that country in 
1986 and are to end this december in brussels the negotiations 
involve about 100 countries and are designed to reduce barriers to 
trade 
us officials estimate that ending the farm subsidies could 
boost us agricultural exports by 11 billion annually 
common market officials say the subsidies can be reduced but not 
eliminated because so many small farmers depend on them 
earlier at the forum andreas van agt european community 
ambassador to the united states said europe would not agree 
unrealistic solutions that are politically unachievable such as 
abandoning subsidies 
among the areas of discussion held up by the deadlock are 
textiles and services 
third world countries want fewer barriers to textile trade the 
united states under pressure from the domestic textile industry 
has been seeking less comprehensive reduction of existing tariffs 
and quotas gatt doesnt cover textile trade which is handled by 
the multifiber agreement between about 80 countries 
the united states however is seeking to have gatt cover 
financial services poorer countries are opposed to gatt regulation 
of banking investment and insurance so they can protect their 
infant financial industries 
the next formal meeting of negotiators is scheduled for july 23 
in geneva switzerland 
