<TEXT>
officials of the central banks of japan 
france england and the united states expressed confidence wednesday 
in the ability of west germanys central bank to control inflation 
after east and west germany merge their currencies next month 
there has been concern that the plan could lead to inflation in 
west germany because east germans will be able to exchange some of 
their nononvertible ostmarks for the west german mark leading to a 
vast increase in the spending power of east germans 
inflation in west germany the dominant economy in europe could 
force the nations central bank the bundesbank to raise interest 
rates that could unsettle world financial markets and lead to 
higher rates in other countries 
but central bankers gathered at the annual international monetary 
conference told reporters they are unconcerned about that prospect 
because of the careful plans for monetary unification laid out by 
the west german government 
robin leighpemberton governor of the bank of england said he 
believes there will be a 10 percent increase in west germanys money 
supply as a result of much of east germanys currency being 
converted into marks that increase is roughly equal to the expected 
rise in the gross domestic product of the nations due to the 
unification he saidso it looks as though the immediate monetary 
situation is one of match and therefore the immediate effect on 
interest rates may be neutral he said 
he said the bundesbank has been confronted with a novel 
difficult political situation and in my opinion theyve handled it 
extremely well 
jacques de larosiere governor of the bank of france said the 
way this process is being handled the rapidity of the elaboration 
of the monetary unification treaty the way things have been 
carved out in terms of the monetary devices all goes well for the 
stability of system and for interest rates 
takeshi ohta deputy governor of the bank of japan said he also 
was confident about the ability of west germanys monetary 
authorities to ensure a smooth transition to a unified currency 
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan said world interest 
rates already have a presumed forecast for the impact of the 
monetary unification but that many unknown factors remain 
there are a number of market forces that are involved in this 
process which will override whatever particular agreements are 
made he said 
it is quite conceivable that to the extent that events 
deviate from the markets expectations that rates either in germany 
or elsewhere could either go up or down he added 
bundesbank president karl otto pohl originally was scheduled to 
attend the session but canceled several weeks ago apparently due to 
constraints on his time in the face of the unification plan 
conference organizers said the conference brought together 
government and commercial bankers from 22 nations 
on another topic greenspan was asked why the federal reserve has 
not acted recently to ease us interest rates in light of signs of 
domestic economic weakness 
the signs in the economy at this stage are really quite 
ambiguous in that respect he said 
he said it is true that the rate of economic growth is 
exceptionally slow but that the unemployment rate has hardly 
changed in recent months 
what we are seeing is a really quite unusual phenomenon 
namely very slow labor force growth and a corresponding rather slow 
economy associated with it but we do not as yet see any underlying 
economic deterioration he said 
