<TEXT>
greyhound refugees left in the dust by a 
3monthold strike of the only nationwide bus line are turning to 
planes trains and automobiles and analysts say the survival of 
coasttocoast bus travel is in jeopardy 
greyhound has vowed to continue service with replacement drivers 
while trying to reorganize its finances under bankruptcy las but 
many people are choosing alternate transportation 
some bus riders are paying more finding it harder to make 
connections and having to stay overnight where the prestrike 
greyhound schedule allowed them to return the same day 
bus industry officials say they see little concern in washington 
over the state of interstate bus travel 
i havent received a single call from any legislator mayor 
governor or anyone complaining about a lack of service because of 
the greyhound strike said wayne j smith executive director of 
the united bus operators of america 
jeremy kahn a washington lawyer who represents scores of bus 
lines said bus travel is ignored because congressmen and 
newspaper people dont ride the bus 
most travelers affected by the strike are rural poor or elderly 
he said this is not a very vocal constituency 
kahn said that whatever results from the strike and mondays 
bankruptcy filing the greyhound of the future will be considerably 
scaled down 
if greyhound goes down it probably will be virtually 
impossible to go from coast to coast by bus said john sim 
another lawyer who has represented bus companies for 40 years 
greyhound says its continuing to run buses to communities that 
provided 98 percent of its revenue last year but the use other 
modes of transportation is increasing 
amtrak ridership is up 12 percent over last year with increases 
of 30 percent or more on some routes spokesman cliff black said 
train travel was booming before the strike but added we have 
gathered some greyhound refugees and made them our own 
car travel is expected to increase 2 percent this summer said 
american automobile association spokesman geoffrey sundstrom but he 
said its impossible to tell how much of that if any will result 
from the greyhound strike 
airline travel is also up and a summer fare war has made some 
trips more affordable for people who might have taken the bus 
several small bus companies report increased ridership 
more than a dozen bus lines have been granted new routes by the 
interstate commerce commission since the strike began 
we were getting a fair share of the traveling public before the 
strike said phil mcbride of peter pan bus lines in springfield 
mass now were getting the lions share 
