<TEXT>
commercial bankers have asked federal 
regulators to bend capital rules to help them work out of problems 
with troubled real estate loans a newspaper reported 
bankers on the federal reserve boards advisory council sought 
help at a closeddoor meeting on may 3 with the feds board of 
governors usa today said in wednesdays edition the newspaper said 
it obtained secret minutes of the meeting 
the bankers suggested that the governors allow banks to take real 
estate losses over a period of years easing the squeeze on bank 
earnings and allowing them more time to set aside reserves the 
newspaper said 
they also suggested relaxing capital rules to allow banks to hold 
and manage troubled real estate loans without a big increase in 
capital the newspaper said 
one council member said the fed governors did not respond to the 
requests some members delivered the suggestion and the governors 
listened intently ronald steinhart chairman of team bank 
dallas was quoted as saying 
theyre asking for forebearance thats exactly what got the 
savings and loans into trouble said lee cross spokeswoman for 
the office of the comptroller of the currency which regulates the 
nations banks 
william seidman chairman of the federal deposit insurance corp 
said bankers have requested similar breaks from his agency it 
needs to be explored he was quoted as saying but he sees no need 
for such breaks now 
the 12 council members head some of the nations biggest banks 
and meet with the fed governors four times a year fed spokesman 
joseph coyne said minutes of the meetings usually are not released 
publicly for three years 
</TEXT>
