<TEXT>
the federal deposit insurance corp said it had 
declined an unsolicited offer for its 26 percent stake of chicagos 
continental corp a move that angered the banks officials 
fdic spokesman alan whitney on tuesday declined to reveal the 
amount of the offer or the investors who made it except to say they 
included the bank itself and certain members of its management he 
said the offer was made in the last several days 
im dumbfounded that in a little more than six months the fdic 
has passed up two legitimate offers to sell its minority interest in 
continental continental chairman thomas c theobald said tuesday 
not only have they failed to turn their asset into cash but 
their continued ownership in a healthy bank is a wholly unwarranted 
role for a regulator 
the fdic became a shareholder of continental after rescuing the 
former continental illinois national bank and trust co in 1984 the 
rescue was expected at the time to cost the federal agency 45 
billion but continentals return to profitability has drastically 
reduced estimates of the cost 
in a brief announcement from washington the fdic said it had 
rejected the latest offer for its continental holdings but still 
remains committed to realizing full value for them it said it would 
explore all options for divesting its stake 
since the 1984 bailout the fdic has made three sales of its 
continental common stock selling 125 million shares in november 
1986 another 125 million shares in december 1988 and 9 million 
shares in august 1989 
